## Understanding matrisies: linear space

  * $V_R$ --- linear space over $R$ --- scalars
  * Has operations: sum, multiply by scalar
  * Linear closure: $<v^{(1)}, \ldots, v^{(n)}> = \{\alpha_1 v^{(1)}1 + \ldots + \alpha_n v^{(n)}, \alpha_i \in R \} \subset V_R$
  * Basis --- minimal $<v_1, \ldots, v_n> = V_R$
  * $\dim V = n$ if $<v_1, \ldots, v_n> = V_R$

  . . .

  __Ex__: $R = \mathbb{R}, V = \mathbb{R}^n$. Vectors are $v = (v_1, \ldots, v_n)$. Standard basis:
  $$e_1 = (1, 0, \ldots, 0)$$
  $$e_2 = (0, 1, \ldots, 0)$$
  $$e_n = (0, \ldots, 0, 1)$$
  $$e_i^{(j)} = \delta_{ij}$$

## Understanding matricies: linear mapping

  __Def__: $f \colon X_R \to Y_R$ is linear, iff $f(\alpha x + \beta y) = \alpha f(x) + \beta f(y)$.

  __Th__: Let $L(X, Y)$ be a set of all linear mappings $X_R \to Y_R$, $n = \dim X$, $m = \dim Y$.
          Than $L(X, Y) = M(n, m, R)$ (up to isomorphism).

